In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims May 15 to May 21, 2011, as Emergency Medical Services (EMS) Week. He acknowledges the important role of EMS personnel in providing timely medical care and saving lives. The article highlights the dedication of emergency medical technicians (EMTs), paramedics, and first responders, as well as other individuals involved in the EMS system such as emergency dispatchers, physicians, nurses, and researchers. The article also mentions the James Zadroga 9/11 Health and Compensation Act, which provides medical monitoring and treatment for rescue and recovery workers affected by the World Trade Center disaster. Obama emphasizes the need to ensure that all children have access to high-quality EMS care through the Federal EMS for Children program. He recognizes EMS agencies as integral to the nation's health security strategy and encourages Americans to support their local EMS providers and improve personal safety and preparedness.